pageSummaryWhat: Staff have set their own wellbeing challenge

story:
Macmillan Cancer Support have very recently supported/are currently supporting several relatives and members of our school community. They provide excellent care which we would like to collectively thank them for by raising as much money as possible at a time when they are unable to run their usual fundraising events. School staff have each set themselves a health/wellbeing goal to achieve in October. These range from giving up alcohol/snacks to running/cycling/walking/rowing a target distance. Please sponsor them to achieve their goals. We would love it if you could donate in a way that means each charity receives an equal amount of money.

Thanks for supporting our fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

pageSummary: Join our quest to Move For Macmillan because we want to raise money for our charity partner.
pageSummaryWhat: Join our quest to Move For Macmillan
pageSummaryWhy: we want to raise money for our charity partner.
story:
Join our quest to Move For Macmillan from 19th October until 1st November to raise money for our charity partner of the year.

When? 19th October – 1st November
What? Walk, Run, Cycle, steps around the home/garden, walking with children (doubles your distance), anything that involves you moving about!

How? All you need to do is donate £10 in the following and join the #moveformacmillan Slack channel and post your activities or send privately to Will Ridley.

Why? We want to keep up our fundraising spirits and encourage everyone to keep moving while working remotely, there will be some prizes along the way too!

Sky Betting & Gaming and Macmillan Cancer Support are working together to support more people living with and affected by cancer.The statistics:1 in 2 people in the UK will get a cancer diagnosis in their lifetime. 1000 people will get diagnosed each day in the UK3 million people are living with cancer in the UK today Macmillans ambition is to be there for every person living with cancer and provide them with tailored support when they need it most. Being told you have cancer is life-changing, and having the right support can have a huge impact physically, financially and emotionally. The number of people living with cancer today is nearly 3 million, and this is set to rise to over 5 million by 2040. Sky Betting and Gamings support is needed more than ever.

pageSummary: 147mile Coast to Coast bike ride because they deserve our help to keep helping others
pageSummaryWhy: they deserve our help to keep helping others
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Me and my good friend Josh are doing the Coast to Coast route from Ravenglass, Lake District to Tynemouth Castle, Newcastle over 3 days (8-10 Nov) to say thank you to the wonderful people at Macmillan Cancer Support for looking after my Grandad and my family in the amazing way that they did. 

We are hoping to raise £500 each to help them continue to help others in the way they helped us. Anything you can give to help us achieve this is greatly appreciated. 

Thank you x

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit Rachel's Just Giving page that we have set up in her memory. 

Recently Rachel sadly passed away and we have organised this page so that we can raise money to donate to Macmillan in her name. As you may know, Macmillan provides incredible support for those affected by cancer, whether this is through physical or emotional care, as well as providing important advice. Rachel completed a huge amount of fundraising for this charity and it was a cause that was always close to her heart which is why we have chosen it for donations. 

This is a difficult time for everyone but would really appreciate any donations that you can give.

pageSummaryWhy: Of team that help my Dad when he needed help.
story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

On 7th November 2020 I shall be attempting to cycle the hight of Mt Everest. 29029ft in one single ride. This is called Everesting. This should take me approximately 30 hours. Starting at 7am on 7/11/2020 and hopeful finish on 8/11/2020. I shall Be doing this in Trinidad and Tobago On a mountain called Morne La Croix. I shall be climbing the same climb approximately 22 times to achieve the hight necessary. I can not sleep but I can rest for short breaks to eat and hydrate during the entire challenge. 

I am attempting this challenge in honor of my farther Christopher Downes, who sadly passed away from cancer. I promised him I would do what I can to help the wonderful people from the Macmillan team that helped him when he needed help the most. 

Dad was a cycling enthusiast and I am sure would be proud if I can pull this one off and also be able to keep my promise of doing what I can for the Macmillan team . 

I look forward to hopefully being able to tell you I was able to complete this challenge. It’s going to be a rough one!!!!

pageSummary: Walking the 10km - 'Do Ron Run' - Well Walk because they have been hugely supportive to our family
pageSummaryWhat: Walking the 10km - 'Do Ron Run' - Well Walk
pageSummaryWhy: they have been hugely supportive to our family
story:
Ron Jackson sadly passed away this September aged 73, Ron (Dad, Grandad, Brother, Husband, Friend, Mentor) was a quite natured person who managed to create a massively positive impact on so many peoples lives, throughout both his home and work life, yet never expected anything in return.

Brian, Ron's brother, came up with an awesome idea for us to be able to celebrate Ron's life, get some exercise and raise some money for an excellent cause, by creating the 'Do Ron Run' which is a ten kilometre walk from Goring Gap (Ferring end) to Steyne Gardens and  back.

Poignantly this event is being held on Ron's Birthday - 15th November - There is going to be wide family turnout, spanning all generations, and is open for anyone to join us (adhering to current Covid guidelines).

Event: Do Ron Run

Date: 15th November 2020

Start: 10:30 Goring Gap (Ferring end) 

Thanks for supporting our fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. story:
Thank you for visiting my page - as many of you know, 20 months ago my dad collasped suddenly and died from a heart attack. He couldn't be saved despite the amazing medical team who tried for hours. Not a day goes by when I don't think about him and  wish I could see him and talk to him. 

On 5th november he would have turned 73 so I am cycling 73km on his memory to raise money for the British Heart Foundation. I miss my dad so much - he was one of a kind and if  by raising funds for BHF I can help someone else be saved from the pain of losing a loved one ,then it's all worthwhile. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:

We are the world’s largest charity dedicated to saving lives through research.

charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
pageSummary: We are taking part in a school fundraising event because it is a charity we all feel strongly about.
pageSummaryWhat: We are taking part in a school fundraising event
pageSummaryWhy: it is a charity we all feel strongly about.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

We are a sixth form form group at Kings Langley Secondary School aiming to raise at least £800 for Cancer Research. 

Cancer Research UK transforms and saves lives. The goal of studying cancer is to develop safe and effective methods to prevent, detect, diagnose, treat, and, ultimately, cure cancer, a disease that has a huge impact on approximately 1 in 2 people throughout their lifetime. 

Throughout the months of October 2020 to March 2021, we will be hosting various fundraising events and raising awareness of the importance for Cancer Research.

As a disease that has touched many of us personally, and millions of others, we feel that it is imperative we continue to help fund the vital research and save lives. On top of this, the current pandemic has had a particularly significant impact on cancer patients as not only do they have to endure the distress of the disease but live with the fear of contracting Covid-19.

Any donations of any quantity would be highly appreciated. 

Thank you

story:

pageSummary: Christmas Charity Raffle because We want to give our support for a good cause
pageSummaryWhy: We want to give our support for a good cause
story:
At Blush Boutique and Beauty we are doing a Christmas Charity Raffle.

There are a total of 6 treatments up for grabs! Including a Lash Lift and Tint (LVL) with Amy worth £38, a Sienna X Spray Tan with Amy (worth £20), Gel fingers or toes with Kirsty (worth £20+), A full set of acrylics with Kirsty (worth £30+ Includes a full set of acrylics with a colour finish, any designs/extras are NOT included in giveaway so will cost extra), a full set of Eyelash Extensions with Shannon (worth up to £55) and finally a Brow Lamination with Shannon (worth £35).

We will pick 6 winners, one everyday from the 1st Dec 2020-6th Dec  

 The First winner will get drawn on the 1st Dec, and will get first pick of any treatment stated above. This will then be taken off the prize draw and each next ticket drawn every day after will choose a treatment until they are all gone. (One treatment per ticket- once the treatment is chosen it is no longer available).

We want to do our bit by supporting the community and wider world by raising money to help those who are currently fighting cancer, those who have fought cancer, and those who are sadly missed. The money will go towards finding new cures, equipment/research for such an amazing and worthy cause. By using our talents, we want to contribute to an amazing cause whilst making our customers happy and giving them an exciting chance to win a treatment worth up to £55! December is the perfect time to pamper yourself and relax! 

We are ALL in this together and we WILL kick Cancers But!! 

In Loving Memory of Gillian Wright, a wonderful Aunt and Sister🎀

In Love and Support of Claire Hall, a beautiful Soul recently diagnosed with Breast Cancer age 31 and currently kicking Cancer’s 🍑!

The tickets will be drawn on Friday 11th of December 2020! If the treatment you pick is not suitable for you, you can donate it to a friend or family member. 

Once picking your raffle, you will have 48 hours to confirm and choose a treatment, otherwise we will pick an alternative winner. Treatments cannot be exchanged and you must use your winning prize within 30 days of winning.

charity.description: Sightsavers' vision is of a world where no one is blind from avoidable causes and where visually impaired people participate equally in society.
charity.name: Sightsavers
story:
William and I are saddened to tell you that our beloved Mother passed away peacefully on Sunday evening at the age of 94. The funeral took place at Chichester Crematorium on Friday 16th October and with the current Covid restrictions we were unable to celebrate her life as we would have wished.

Joan was the youngest of two sisters, born in Ely and growing up in Soham in Cambridgeshire. In 1942, at the age of 16, she contracted Diphtheria and was admitted to the Isolation Hospital at Exning with her Mother, Violet; her sister, Phyllis, soon joined them. Her Mother died in the June and Joan and Phyllis had to remain in hospital for another month and were unable to attend the funeral.

Joan married in 1952 and William and I were welcomed soon afterwards. In 1958 the family moved to Selsey. Phyllis remained in Soham until 2006, when she surprised us by marrying for the first time at the age of 83 and moving to Selsey. Phyllis had always suffered from poor eyesight and was registered blind. When her husband died in 2010 Phyllis went to live with Joan and they looked after each other until Phyllis died in October 2013. 

Joan and Phyllis' cousin Joyce also suffers from macular degeneration and is registered blind; all three of them supported 'Sightsavers' as they realised how vulnerable they all felt with failing eyesight and wanted to help prevent avoidable sight-loss for others.

William and I requested that there were no flowers at the funeral - Janet made a coffin spray from Mother's garden - but donations in Joan's memory may be made via Dillistone and Wraight in Chichester or via JustGiving.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
